<emphasis id="A6A02439FFF8160015D1F87EFE77F862" bold="true" box="[385,401,2005,2029]" pageId="6" pageNumber="598">I.</emphasis>
Ventrite VIII and spiculum; 
<emphasis id="A6A02439FFF8160016E4F87EFD21F862" bold="true" box="[692,711,2005,2029]" pageId="6" pageNumber="598">J.</emphasis>
Ovipositor.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFF916011497FF3CFF1EFF76" blockId="7.[151,1436,150,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">Elytra ovoid, about 1.5× longer than wide in dorsal view, humerus strongly narrowed, widest at apical 2/5, disc with regular rows of foveolated large, shallow punctures; scutellum transverse, nearly triangular; wings completely reduced.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFF916011497FEA8FA81FE22" blockId="7.[151,1436,150,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">
Metaventrite and abdomen finely covered with short thin setae and dense small punctures; median sulcus distinct, extending from anterior margin to ca. 3/4 of metaventrite length. Abdominal ventrite I longest, shorter than combined lengths of ventrites III and IV; ventrite II longer than metaventrite III; metaventrites III and IV distinctly concave; ventrite V slightly shorter than combined lengths of ventrites III and IV, apex rounded; apical margin of abdominal ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFF9160115E0FE38FDEEFE22" box="[432,520,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[185,1423,597,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-196@6.[163,1423,597,1909]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) yeziyangi sp. nov., A–H, male, I–J, female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Abdominal ventrite VIII; E. Spiculum gastrale; F. Aedeagus, ventral view; G. Same, dorsal view; H. Same, lateral view; I. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; J. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598182" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598182/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
) medially impressed, posterior and lateral margins bearing sparse long setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFF916011497FE1CFE68FDB2" blockId="7.[151,1436,150,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">Femora claviform medially, expanded in distal halves; all tibiae covered with brown setae apically; pro- and mesotibiae weakly curved, metatibia straight; tarsomeres simple, apical pro- and mesotarsomeres about as long as combined lengths of proximal four tarsomeres, apical metatarsomere shorter than combined lengths of proximal three metatarsomeres.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="946BF82BFFF916011497FDECFD60FD0A" blockId="7.[151,1436,150,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFF916011517FDECFE23FDEE" box="[327,453,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[185,1423,597,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-196@6.[163,1423,597,1909]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) yeziyangi sp. nov., A–H, male, I–J, female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Abdominal ventrite VIII; E. Spiculum gastrale; F. Aedeagus, ventral view; G. Same, dorsal view; H. Same, lateral view; I. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; J. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598182" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598182/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">Figs 4F–H</figureCitation>
) symmetrical in dorsal view, distinctly curved in profile; spiculum gastrale (
<figureCitation id="0CEFE4AEFFF91601116CFDECFA72FDEE" box="[1340,1428,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[185,1423,597,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-196@6.[163,1423,597,1909]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Diagnostic features of H. (H.) yeziyangi sp. nov., A–H, male, I–J, female. A. Head and pronotum; B. Pronotum, lateral view; C. Antenna; D. Abdominal ventrite VIII; E. Spiculum gastrale; F. Aedeagus, ventral view; G. Same, dorsal view; H. Same, lateral view; I. Ventrite VIII and spiculum; J. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6598182" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6598182/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="599">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
) asymmetrical, short, with large apical lobes.
</paragraph>
